    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-12-17T17:32:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-12-17T17:32:00-05:00" n="100"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d100">
                <head>100. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Libya</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d100fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                            target="#t_PET1">PET</gloss> 15–2 LIBYA. Secret; Priority. Drafted by
                            <persName>Harry I. Odell</persName> (<gloss target="#t_AFN1"
                            >AF/N</gloss>); cleared by <persName corresp="#p_BGS1">Brown</persName>
                        and <persName>Scott George</persName> (<gloss target="#t_EURBMI1"
                            >EUR/BMI</gloss>); and approved by <persName corresp="#p_SRS1">Robert S.
                            Smith</persName> (<gloss target="#t_AF1">AF</gloss>). Repeated to London
                        and Benghazi.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-12-17T22:32:00+00:00">December 17, 1971,
                        2232Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>227215. Subject: <gloss target="#t_BP1">BP</gloss> Nationalization. References:
                    (A) State 226700; (B) Tripoli 2302.<note n="2" xml:id="d100fn2">Telegram 226700
                        to London, December 17, summarized below, is ibid. Telegram 2302 is <ref
                            target="#d99">Document 99</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Your penetrating, helpful and most timely analysis very much
                        appreciated.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>After careful consideration at highest levels, Dept has decided adopt
                        following position: <list>
                            <label>(a)</label>
                            <item>There will be no public statement by <gloss target="#t_USG1"
                                    >USG</gloss>.</item>
                            <label>(b)</label>
                            <item>Dept has indicated to Dept of Justice that it will not object if
                                oil companies are permitted take concerted action to apply Libyan
                                sharing agreement and to inhibit marketing of <gloss target="#t_BP1"
                                    >BP</gloss> oil by <gloss target="#t_LARG1">LARG</gloss> (N.B.,
                                this is extent of oil companies’ request to Dept to date).</item>
                            <label>(c)</label>
                            <item>As indicated State 226700, <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss>
                                will support <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> démarches to major
                                consuming countries by private and confidential démarches to major
                                consuming countries and will adopt similar position at <gloss
                                    target="#t_OECD1">OECD</gloss> oil committee meeting in
                                January.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>You will receive separate instructions regarding possible representations
                        to <gloss target="#t_LARG1">LARG</gloss> on general question of
                        nationalization, in light your comments in para 8 of Tripoli 2302.<note
                            n="3" xml:id="d100fn3">These instructions stated that because the
                            companies had not asked for <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>
                            intervention, and because of timing, the Department believed that the
                            Embassy’s suggestions would “clearly link <gloss target="#t_USG1"
                                >USG</gloss> with <gloss target="#t_BP1">BP</gloss> problem in
                                <gloss target="#t_LARG1">LARG</gloss>’s mind. Libyans might well
                            interpret it as support for British hardline position or might get
                            impression of weakness or fear on our part re future of <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">US</gloss> companies, neither of which could work to
                            our or companies’ benefit.” (Telegram 1346 to Tripoli, January 5, 1972;
                            National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files
                            1970–73, <gloss target="#t_PET1">PET</gloss> 15–2 LIBYA)</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rogers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
